How to talk like a certain school of philosophy¶

Name : Ting Han Ko
Uni: tk2944

Philosophy is not an easy topic and it is not easy to speak like one. This project is dedicated to help someone who's interested in identifying different schools and try to speak like one. To begin with, I do not have any philosophical training or education profound enough to allow me to make judgement on how to speak like a philosopher. However, I was thinking perhaps we can all learn something mechanically from the data. We will ask the computer to read those senteces for us even before we understand what it actually means, and then computer could tell us what can possibly be the characteristics of each school.

Through the analysis maybe we could learn philosophy in a more efficient way and we could even provide this result to expert and see if they agree with our findings. Eventually, I would like to see if I can talk like a certain school.

1. About the data¶

This dataset was obtained from kaggle, which was originally collected and used for the Philosophy Data Project and that website. The former philosophy teacher, Kourosh Alizadeh, made the data publicly available so others could work with it.

The dataset contains over 300,000 sentences from over 50 texts spanning 13 major schools of philosophy. The represented schools are: 'analytic', 'aristotle', 'capitalism', 'communism', 'continental', 'empiricism', 'feminism', 'german_idealism', 'nietzsche', 'phenomenology', 'plato', 'rationalism', 'stoicism'

1a. Data Cleaning and processing¶

The data was originally processed and cleaned by the professor Kourosh Alizadeh who kindly provided the data to all the data scientists.

The data will be used in two format here- one that will be used here was processed by combining all the senteces within one school; the other one was processed by taking the average of the length of sentence of eacah school, as it will be shown later below.

3. Length of senteces¶

In addition to the content, perhaps we could also adjust the length of our sentences to sound more like a true philosopher. First, we will need to see how many words. Since according to a scientist Wolf Garbe the average word length in English language is 4.7 characters, we will use this as a reference to see roughly how many words we should say in a sentence to achieve the result.

Let's first look at the average length of sentence and find out who talk the most and the less.

takeaway #3¶

This tells us that capitalism talk the most in one sentence and plato talk the least. We can also utilize this for other schools. For example, to continue my learning journey for empiricism, I would say I shoud talk more than I used to and should include almost 40 words on average everytime in my sentence.

4. Sentiment Analysis¶

Now we can move to a deeper concept-- what kind of sentiment is represented in each school? It is not enough for us just to simply look at a few words and the length, now we're going to also look at the overall positivity and subjectivity of the content. Below shows the analysis plot of subjectivity and polarity overview:

takeaway #4¶

From this graph we can see a few schools are more closely positioned with one another. Interestingly, communism is more objective compared to otehr schools, and plato seems to be the most positive one in comparison. If I want to talk like a empiricism, according to the graph, I will just pick the most middle ground for every speech and try to be only moderately positive and moderately subjective.

For another example, to continue my journey of speaking like a empiricism, I would have to talk mention sex and female more.

Conclusion¶

There are a lot of information we can extract from the analysis. To simply answer my question in the beginning, how to talk like a specific school?, we can narrow it down to a few points below:

  1. Choose the right topics: communism, capitalism --> economics ; idealism --> Concepts
  2. Choose a right length to talk: capitalism, empiricism --> long ; Plato, Nietzsche --> short
  3. Choose the right attitude: Plato, Stoicism --> positive ; continental --> negative
  4. Choose a good word and use frequently: Analytics --> 'case'

Hopefully someone study philosophy can comment on whether this is a fair result or not!
